<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1468,2033]" pageId="16" pageNumber="311">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1612,1637]" pageId="16" pageNumber="311">Description</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[352,435,1612,1637]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1733,1755]" captionTargetBox="[304,1283,498,1669]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[281,1306,483,1695]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 12. Antarctotetilla pilosa nov. sp. A, B. Holotype from South Orkneys (CEAB.POR.BIO.502a ANT 27211). C. A. pilosa after desiccation, arrows point to the long hairy hispidation caused by long fusiform oxeas, protriaenes and sometimes anatriaenes (from Carella et al. 2016). D. Area surrounding the osculum, arrows point to the osculum. E. Arrows point to the pores grouped in small surface depressions. F. Transversal section." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457246/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="311">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). Globular, 
<quantity box="[567,621,1613,1637]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="311" unit="cm" value="8.0">8 cm</quantity>
in diameter sponge (
<figureCitation box="[855,1040,1612,1637]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1733,1755]" captionTargetBox="[304,1283,498,1669]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[281,1306,483,1695]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 12. Antarctotetilla pilosa nov. sp. A, B. Holotype from South Orkneys (CEAB.POR.BIO.502a ANT 27211). C. A. pilosa after desiccation, arrows point to the long hairy hispidation caused by long fusiform oxeas, protriaenes and sometimes anatriaenes (from Carella et al. 2016). D. Area surrounding the osculum, arrows point to the osculum. E. Arrows point to the pores grouped in small surface depressions. F. Transversal section." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457246/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="311">Fig. 12a, b and c</figureCitation>
).Long hairy hispidation protruding up to 
<quantity box="[218,278,1649,1673]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="311" unit="cm" value="2.0">2 cm</quantity>
, throughout the surface, caused by long fusiform oxeas, protriaenes, and sometimes anatriaenes. This hispidation becomes much longer (up to 
<quantity box="[613,671,1685,1709]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="16" pageNumber="311" unit="cm" value="4.0">4 cm</quantity>
) after sponge desiccation due to flesh retraction. Oscules of several sizes spread on the sponge body (
<figureCitation box="[542,643,1720,1745]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1733,1755]" captionTargetBox="[304,1283,498,1669]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[281,1306,483,1695]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 12. Antarctotetilla pilosa nov. sp. A, B. Holotype from South Orkneys (CEAB.POR.BIO.502a ANT 27211). C. A. pilosa after desiccation, arrows point to the long hairy hispidation caused by long fusiform oxeas, protriaenes and sometimes anatriaenes (from Carella et al. 2016). D. Area surrounding the osculum, arrows point to the osculum. E. Arrows point to the pores grouped in small surface depressions. F. Transversal section." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457246/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="311">Fig. 12d</figureCitation>
). Pores grouped in more or less deep surface depressions (
<figureCitation box="[1324,1423,1720,1745]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1733,1755]" captionTargetBox="[304,1283,498,1669]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[281,1306,483,1695]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 12. Antarctotetilla pilosa nov. sp. A, B. Holotype from South Orkneys (CEAB.POR.BIO.502a ANT 27211). C. A. pilosa after desiccation, arrows point to the long hairy hispidation caused by long fusiform oxeas, protriaenes and sometimes anatriaenes (from Carella et al. 2016). D. Area surrounding the osculum, arrows point to the osculum. E. Arrows point to the pores grouped in small surface depressions. F. Transversal section." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457246/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="311">Fig. 12e</figureCitation>
). Pseudocortex (
<figureCitation box="[322,416,1756,1781]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1733,1755]" captionTargetBox="[304,1283,498,1669]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[281,1306,483,1695]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 12. Antarctotetilla pilosa nov. sp. A, B. Holotype from South Orkneys (CEAB.POR.BIO.502a ANT 27211). C. A. pilosa after desiccation, arrows point to the long hairy hispidation caused by long fusiform oxeas, protriaenes and sometimes anatriaenes (from Carella et al. 2016). D. Area surrounding the osculum, arrows point to the osculum. E. Arrows point to the pores grouped in small surface depressions. F. Transversal section." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457246/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="311">Fig. 12f</figureCitation>
) composed of loose auxiliary oxeas perpendicular to the sponge surface. Megascleres: oxeas, protriaenes, anatriaenes, and trichodal protriaenes; microscleres: sigmaspires. A basal root-tuft system of anatriaenes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1468,2033]" lastBlockId="17.[151,1437,151,429]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="312" pageId="16" pageNumber="311">
Spicules (
<figureCitation box="[309,392,1864,1889]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1320,1342]" captionTargetBox="[387,1194,495,1216]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[324,1263,453,1264]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 13. Spicules of Antarctotetilla pilosa nov. sp. (holotype, CEAB.POR.BIO.502a ANT 27211). A. Terminal part of large fusiform oxea I. B. Auxiliary secondary oxea II. C. Medium size protriaene II. D. Large Protriaene I. E. Small anatriaene II. F. Large anatriaene I. G. Thick anatriaene III. H. Trichodal protriaene. I. Sigmaspire." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457248/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="311">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
; 
<tableCitation box="[404,486,1864,1889]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="5.[147,224,485,505]" captionText="TABLE 1. Spicule measurements (in μm) of the Antarctic Tetillidae species studied. Maximum and minimum values correspond to the average of the several individuals measured (from 1 to 5, depending on the species)." pageId="16" pageNumber="311">Table 1</tableCitation>
). Megascleres: oxeas I (
<figureCitation box="[760,854,1864,1889]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1320,1342]" captionTargetBox="[387,1194,495,1216]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[324,1263,453,1264]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 13. Spicules of Antarctotetilla pilosa nov. sp. (holotype, CEAB.POR.BIO.502a ANT 27211). A. Terminal part of large fusiform oxea I. B. Auxiliary secondary oxea II. C. Medium size protriaene II. D. Large Protriaene I. E. Small anatriaene II. F. Large anatriaene I. G. Thick anatriaene III. H. Trichodal protriaene. I. Sigmaspire." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457248/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="311">Fig. 13a</figureCitation>
) large and fusiform: 4050–7682.5–10950 µm 
<date box="[1373,1421,1864,1889]" pageId="16" pageNumber="311" value="1935-10">x 35</date>
– 83.5–120 µm. Auxiliary small oxeas II (
<figureCitation box="[617,718,1900,1925]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1320,1342]" captionTargetBox="[387,1194,495,1216]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[324,1263,453,1264]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 13. Spicules of Antarctotetilla pilosa nov. sp. (holotype, CEAB.POR.BIO.502a ANT 27211). A. Terminal part of large fusiform oxea I. B. Auxiliary secondary oxea II. C. Medium size protriaene II. D. Large Protriaene I. E. Small anatriaene II. F. Large anatriaene I. G. Thick anatriaene III. H. Trichodal protriaene. I. Sigmaspire." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457248/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="311">Fig. 13b</figureCitation>
): 630– 
<date box="[798,922,1900,1925]" pageId="16" pageNumber="311" value="1137" valueMax="1780">1137–1780</date>
µm x 12.5–22.4–35 µm. Anatriaenes I (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1320,1342]" captionTargetBox="[387,1194,495,1216]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[324,1263,453,1264]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 13. Spicules of Antarctotetilla pilosa nov. sp. (holotype, CEAB.POR.BIO.502a ANT 27211). A. Terminal part of large fusiform oxea I. B. Auxiliary secondary oxea II. C. Medium size protriaene II. D. Large Protriaene I. E. Small anatriaene II. F. Large anatriaene I. G. Thick anatriaene III. H. Trichodal protriaene. I. Sigmaspire." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457248/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="311">Fig. 13f</figureCitation>
): 7180–12460–16880 µm x 22.5–24.5–27.5 µm in size with long and thin clades: 160–190.5–210 µm long; rhabdomes fusiform, thicker at the middle and filiform at the terminal part. Anatriaenes II: 3220–3806.7–4960 µm 
<date box="[151,198,2008,2033]" pageId="16" pageNumber="311" value="2015-10">x 15</date>
–17.5–22.5 µm in size (
<figureCitation box="[471,565,2008,2033]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1320,1342]" captionTargetBox="[387,1194,495,1216]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[324,1263,453,1264]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 13. Spicules of Antarctotetilla pilosa nov. sp. (holotype, CEAB.POR.BIO.502a ANT 27211). A. Terminal part of large fusiform oxea I. B. Auxiliary secondary oxea II. C. Medium size protriaene II. D. Large Protriaene I. E. Small anatriaene II. F. Large anatriaene I. G. Thick anatriaene III. H. Trichodal protriaene. I. Sigmaspire." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457248/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="311">Fig. 13e</figureCitation>
) with short clades: 62.5–85.8–130 µm and fusiform rhabdomes. Anatriaenes III (
<figureCitation box="[200,304,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1320,1342]" captionTargetBox="[387,1194,495,1216]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[324,1263,453,1264]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 13. Spicules of Antarctotetilla pilosa nov. sp. (holotype, CEAB.POR.BIO.502a ANT 27211). A. Terminal part of large fusiform oxea I. B. Auxiliary secondary oxea II. C. Medium size protriaene II. D. Large Protriaene I. E. Small anatriaene II. F. Large anatriaene I. G. Thick anatriaene III. H. Trichodal protriaene. I. Sigmaspire." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457248/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="312">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[258,304,152,176]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.3" pageId="17" pageNumber="312" unit="g" value="13.0">13g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
): 4400–10265–14350 x 17.5–24.4–27.5 µm in size with thick, 70–117.6 –140 µm long clades; rhabdomes fusiform, thicker at middle and filiform at the terminal part. Protriaenes I (
<figureCitation box="[1151,1252,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1320,1342]" captionTargetBox="[387,1194,495,1216]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[324,1263,453,1264]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 13. Spicules of Antarctotetilla pilosa nov. sp. (holotype, CEAB.POR.BIO.502a ANT 27211). A. Terminal part of large fusiform oxea I. B. Auxiliary secondary oxea II. C. Medium size protriaene II. D. Large Protriaene I. E. Small anatriaene II. F. Large anatriaene I. G. Thick anatriaene III. H. Trichodal protriaene. I. Sigmaspire." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457248/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="312">Fig. 13d</figureCitation>
): 4300–6986.2– 10880 µm 
<date box="[279,415,224,248]" pageId="17" pageNumber="312" value="1940-10-20" valueMax="1940-10-30" valueMin="1940-10-20">x 20–30–40</date>
µm with clades: 100–181.7–260 µm long, usually one clade longer than the other two; rhabdomes tapering from the base of the clades to end in a filamentous termination. Protriaenes II (
<figureCitation box="[1250,1346,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1320,1342]" captionTargetBox="[387,1194,495,1216]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[324,1263,453,1264]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 13. Spicules of Antarctotetilla pilosa nov. sp. (holotype, CEAB.POR.BIO.502a ANT 27211). A. Terminal part of large fusiform oxea I. B. Auxiliary secondary oxea II. C. Medium size protriaene II. D. Large Protriaene I. E. Small anatriaene II. F. Large anatriaene I. G. Thick anatriaene III. H. Trichodal protriaene. I. Sigmaspire." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457248/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="312">Fig. 13c</figureCitation>
): 2400– 2767.5–3250 µm 
<date box="[355,404,295,320]" pageId="17" pageNumber="312" value="2010-10">x 10</date>
–11.9–17.5 µm, with clades: 80–142–240 µm in length, usually one clade longer than the other two; rhabdomes tapering to a filiform end. Trichodal protriaenes (
<figureCitation box="[992,1091,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1320,1342]" captionTargetBox="[387,1194,495,1216]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[324,1263,453,1264]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 13. Spicules of Antarctotetilla pilosa nov. sp. (holotype, CEAB.POR.BIO.502a ANT 27211). A. Terminal part of large fusiform oxea I. B. Auxiliary secondary oxea II. C. Medium size protriaene II. D. Large Protriaene I. E. Small anatriaene II. F. Large anatriaene I. G. Thick anatriaene III. H. Trichodal protriaene. I. Sigmaspire." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457248/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="312">Fig. 13h</figureCitation>
) very small with filamentous rhabdomes: 405–1063.6–2480 µm 
<date box="[561,600,367,392]" pageId="17" pageNumber="312">x 2</date>
–2.6–5 µm long and thin, 10–51.4–175 µm long clades. Microscleres: sigmaspires (
<figureCitation box="[298,390,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1320,1342]" captionTargetBox="[387,1194,495,1216]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[324,1263,453,1264]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 13. Spicules of Antarctotetilla pilosa nov. sp. (holotype, CEAB.POR.BIO.502a ANT 27211). A. Terminal part of large fusiform oxea I. B. Auxiliary secondary oxea II. C. Medium size protriaene II. D. Large Protriaene I. E. Small anatriaene II. F. Large anatriaene I. G. Thick anatriaene III. H. Trichodal protriaene. I. Sigmaspire." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1457248/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="312">
Fig. 
<date box="[351,390,404,429]" pageId="17" pageNumber="312" value="2013-01">13i</date>
</figureCitation>
): 10–11.6–12.5 µm in length.
</paragraph>
